<doc id="3696" url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=3696" title="Demographics of Burundi">
Demographics of Burundi

This article is about the <a href="demographics">demographic</a> features of the <a href="population">population</a> of <a href="Burundi">Burundi</a>, including <a href="population%20density">population density</a>, <a href="Ethnic%20group">ethnicity</a>, education level, health of the populace, economic status, religious affiliations and other aspects of the population.
At 206.1 persons per km²., <a href="Burundi">Burundi</a> has the second-largest <a href="population%20density">population density</a> in Sub-<a href="Sahara">Sahara</a>n <a href="Africa">Africa</a>. Most people live on <a href="farm">farm</a>s near areas of fertile volcanic soil. The population is made up of three major <a href="ethnic%20group">ethnic group</a>s – <a href="Hutu">Hutu</a> ("Bahutu"), <a href="Tutsi">Tutsi</a> ("Batutsi" or "Watusi"), and <a href="Great%20Lakes%20Twa">Twa</a> ("Batwa"). <a href="Kirundi">Kirundi</a> is the common language. Intermarriage takes place frequently between the Hutus and Tutsis. The terms "<a href="pasture">pastoralist</a>" and "<a href="agriculture">agriculturist</a>", often used as ethnic designations for Watusi and Bahutu, respectively, are only occupational titles which vary among individuals and groups. Although Hutus encompass the majority of the population, historically Tutsis have been politically and economically dominant.

According to , the total population was in , compared to only 2 456 000 in 1950. The proportion of children below the age of 15 in 2015 was 44.8%, 52.7% was between 15 and 65 years of age, while 2.5% was older than 65 years old

Numbers are in thousands. UN medium variant projections 

Registration of vital events is in Burundi not complete. The Population Departement of the United Nations prepared the following estimates.

